{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514569"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12334"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12334"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.13,0.42,0.03,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4854"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12334"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42319"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1546"},{"type":"tags","id":"1811"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42739"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of sudden onset painful skin eruption all over his body, fever, and generalised headache. He had presented to his General Practice clinic three days prior with an infected finger from a rose thorn and was commenced on oral flucloxacillin at that time. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications other than the antibiotics, which he had tolerated well previously. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Skin examination reveals well-defined tender pustules and nodules across his body (Images 1-2). A skin biopsy shows a diffuse neutrophilic infiltrate in the reticular dermis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this skin condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Doxycycline","Valaciclovir","Prednisolone","Diclofenac","Dapsone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with Sweet\u0027s syndrome, also known as acute febrile neutrophilic dermatosis. The diagnosis is supported by the sudden onset of typical cutaneous lesions (painful red or blue plaques or nodules) and histopathology showing neutrophilic infiltrate, which are major diagnostic criteria. Minor criteria include fever, association with infection, and leukocytosis. It commonly occurs as a reaction to an underlying condition such as infection, inflammatory bowel disease, pregnancy, or malignancy, and in this case, would have been triggered by the recent infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment for Sweet\u0027s syndrome. Systemic corticosteroids are the first-line therapy due to their potent anti-inflammatory properties. They rapidly suppress the inflammatory response and provide symptomatic relief. Typically, oral prednisolone is given, but topical application may be considered for mild cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapsone\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative treatment if corticosteroids are contraindicated. It is a sulfone drug with anti-inflammatory properties that downregulates neutrophil chemotaxis and reduces the release of leukotrienes and prostaglandins. However, it\u0027s important to rule out G6PD deficiency before starting dapsone therapy due to the risk of haemolysis. Regular monitoring of complete blood counts is necessary for patients on dapsone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E can be used as an adjuvant treatment in Sweet\u0027s syndrome due to its anti-inflammatory properties, but it is not the most effective primary treatment for this condition. As the patient\u0027s rash is not related to the flucloxacillin prescribed for mild cellulitis, there would be no benefit in changing his antibiotic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValaciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment for herpes zoster, which presents with painful vesicles over a dermatomal distribution, not over the whole body as seen in this case. It does not have a role in treating Sweet\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiclofenac\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, may help with symptom relief but is not the most appropriate primary treatment for Sweet\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther steroid-sparing agents that can be considered in the management of Sweet\u0027s syndrome include colchicine, potassium iodide, or immunosuppressants like cyclosporine or methotrexate in refractory cases. It\u0027s also important to identify and treat any underlying trigger or associated condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sweet\u0027s syndrome is characterized by sudden onset of tender plaques or nodules, fever, and neutrophilic infiltration on skin biopsy.","Systemic corticosteroids, such as prednisolone, are the first-line treatment for Sweet\u0027s syndrome due to their potent anti-inflammatory properties.","Sweet\u0027s syndrome can be triggered by infections, inflammatory conditions, or malignancies, and identifying the underlying cause is important for management."],"references":["Vashisht P, Goyal A, Hearth Holmes MP. Sweet Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Sep 12. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431050/","Booth SA, Moody CE, Dahl MV, Herron MJ, Nelson RD. Dapsone suppresses integrin-mediated neutrophil adherence function. J Invest Dermatol. 1992 Feb;98(2):135-40. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1732379/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42319"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12334"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20193"},{"type":"media","id":"20194"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20193"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17d140b9-4884-4daf-9b92-75e61a709903.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17d140b9-4884-4daf-9b92-75e61a709903.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":349}},{"type":"media","id":"20194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20194"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1892322b-2fdd-42c4-ae34-be5099f15fd7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1892322b-2fdd-42c4-ae34-be5099f15fd7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":409}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42319"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-22T10:36:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T10:39:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":